<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-05T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-05T03:00:00-05:00" n="296" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d296">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.1115 Wright, Lucy: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Chefoo</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Webber</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Chefoo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-05T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">April 5,
                                        1927—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 6—10:30
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>In reply to Department’s telegram April 4, 6 p.m.<note n="14" xml:id="d296fn14">Not printed.</note> Miss Lucy Wright and other
                            missionaries Baptist Hospital, Hwanghsien, now safe and well in Chefoo.
                            In view of the uncertainty of conditions, possible break-down
                            communications motor roadway, Chefoo, Weihsien, and recommendation made
                            by Chinese authorities, all women and children and practically all left
                            in the district have come to Chefoo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Webber</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>